	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				   Enchanters initially are the weakest of all spellcasters.  Their focus is Alteration, and all alteration spells cast on creatures have a chance of being resisted.  This means unlike an Evocation spell, when you blast a monster with Sufficating Sphere there's a chance (depending on comparitive levels between you and the monster) the spell will be resisted for absolutely no effect.  And the monster will be angry at you!<BR>
   However behind this weakness lies the little known fact that Enchanters may well be the most powerful spellcaster of all.  At a casual glance the Sufficating Sphere, a level 4 enchanter spell, inflicts a mere 10 damage - if it's not resisted.  Compared the Magician and Wizard spells at level 4 it's about equivilent damage-wise but is neither area affect nor unable to be resisted.  Now cast it on yourself and watch your hitpoints... 10 damage initially but then the damage just keeps going!  Before the Sufficating sphere spell has worn entirely off, it has inflicted no less than *40* damage, and lowered your stats while it was in affect on you - and your just a level 4 enchanter when you cast it!<BR>
   While this is good, the attack spell resistance hurdle is still a tough one to deal with, but fortunately Enchanters gain Chaotic Feedback at level 8, and it's Evocation.  (Unfortunately it's the very first enchanter evocation spell so you'll have to practice it alot before you can cast it reliably without it fizzling.)  Chaotic Feedback inflicts damage that matches the best level 8 Wizard and Magician direct damage spells, so all is well in the Enchanter direct damage world.<BR>
   This is just the tip of the iceburg, however, as Enchanters also get to mess with monster minds.  One of the most expencive but very handy spells you will gain at level 4 is Fear.  This spell allows you to almost always (baring interuption) scare off a monster you are fighting so you can get a head start on a getaway.  Later Whirl Till You Hurl makes a monster sit and spin, and is said to be much more effective than Root.  Chase the Moon is likely an improved verison of fear, perhaps allowing you to make a much longer escape.    This and a variety of other spells can make an Enchanter equally as handy to have in a party as a Wizard.  For example, if that bandit is about to kill off your party, you can scare it away and buy your party time to escape - all a wizard or magician could do is try to kill the bandit like everybody else.<BR>
    The enchanter's non combative abilities aren't bad either.  Enchanters can enchant ore so they can be made into magicial ones (a spell only purchasable in the Dark Elven city it is rumored), they can create the illusion they are another race (allowing you to walze into unfriendly cities), they can turn invisible and see invisible at the earliest level of all classes (lvl 4), and many other handy affects.  This is not to say your the king of utility as an enchanter, but it cirtainly leaves you a few handy options for cirtain situations (mostly public relations).
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
	<tr>
		
